That sounds like a great plan! SwiftUI is designed with componentization in mind, so it's a good idea to break down your UI into reusable components. 

Here's a basic example of how you might structure a chat UI in SwiftUI. This example includes a `MessageRow` component for displaying individual messages, a `MessageListView` for displaying a list of messages, and a `ChatView` that combines the `MessageListView` with a text input field for user input.

```swift
import SwiftUI

struct MessageRow: View {
    var message: String
    var isUser: Bool

    var body: some View {
        HStack {
            if isUser {
                Spacer()
                Text(message)
                    .padding()
                    .background(Color.blue)
                    .foregroundColor(.white)
                    .cornerRadius(10)
            } else {
                Text(message)
                    .padding()
                    .background(Color.gray)
                    .foregroundColor(.white)
                    .cornerRadius(10)
                Spacer()
            }
        }
    }
}

struct MessageListView: View {
    var messages: [(String, Bool)] // Tuple with message and isUser flag

    var body: some View {
        List(messages, id: \.0) { message in
            MessageRow(message: message.0, isUser: message.1)
        }
    }
}

struct ChatView: View {
    @State private var inputText: String = ""
    var messages: [(String, Bool)] // Tuple with message and isUser flag

